I returned to the hut, locked the door, and lit some forget-me-not incense.

It had a very soft and gentle scent.

Konomi and the others' feelings are ingrained in this hut and in my body, and I don't think I'll be able to forget them easily.

The fun days, the times we spent together, his delicate body bouncing in my arms, his warmth. His sensual voice as he moaned for me, his soft hair.

The memory, which he cannot forget no matter how hard he tries, is so vivid that he could easily recall it even if Konomi was not there...

I closed my eyes as I prayed, surrounded by the smoke rising from the incense.

I don't want to forget. The thought of erasing Konomi from my memory would be heartbreaking.

But if I did remember, I'd surely be heartbroken by the days we couldn't see each other.

So maybe it's better to forget about it.

As smoke fills the hut, memories spill out like water spilling through your fingers.

"...ugh...ahh..."

--who is this?

A boy who smiles innocently and brightly, a boy who is stubborn but actually the kindest of people, and a boy who is shy but full of enthusiasm for learning.

And then, a boy smiles, with eyes that seem to see through something that he thinks is more important than anyone else...

What on earth is this incense smell?

Why would I burn incense in a place like this...?

Important things appear and disappear one after another.

How much do I have to forget, what do I have to forget, to be able to forget the smooth, soft feeling of a body on my fingertips?

Surely there are things we must forget...

